    {
        "content": "<p>Yes this is very helpful. I'll add that if you want to do this for land output, there are a couple of small tweaks you have to make based on how things are named. For Line [28] in <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"13\">@Anderson Banihirwe</span> 's code above, I (think) it would be the following: <br>\n<code>ds = ds.assign_coords(time=ds.time_bounds.mean('hist_interval'))</code></p>",
        "id": 30701,
        "sender_full_name": "Katie Dagon",
        "timestamp": 1619806148
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have a function <code>time_set_mid</code> at<br>\n<a href=\"https://github.com/klindsay28/CESM2_coup_carb_cycle_JAMES/blob/22aa55e60471078922d96f07033adb326769e47a/src/utils.py#L69-L103\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://github.com/klindsay28/CESM2_coup_carb_cycle_JAMES/blob/22aa55e60471078922d96f07033adb326769e47a/src/utils.py#L69-L103\">https://github.com/klindsay28/CESM2_coup_carb_cycle_JAMES/blob/22aa55e60471078922d96f07033adb326769e47a/src/utils.py#L69-L103</a><br>\nthat resets <code>time</code> to the midpoints of time bounds. It works if <code>decode_times</code> was True or False, and works with different components of CESM that have different names for the time bounds variables. I also have a test suite for it at<br>\n<a href=\"https://github.com/klindsay28/CESM2_coup_carb_cycle_JAMES/blob/22aa55e60471078922d96f07033adb326769e47a/tests/test_utils.py#L49-L87\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://github.com/klindsay28/CESM2_coup_carb_cycle_JAMES/blob/22aa55e60471078922d96f07033adb326769e47a/tests/test_utils.py#L49-L87\">https://github.com/klindsay28/CESM2_coup_carb_cycle_JAMES/blob/22aa55e60471078922d96f07033adb326769e47a/tests/test_utils.py#L49-L87</a></p>",
        "id": 30705,
        "sender_full_name": "Keith Lindsay",
        "timestamp": 1619807035
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"42\">@Allison Baker</span>, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"47\">@Katie Dagon</span>'s shortcut works</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><span class=\"n\">In</span> <span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">11</span><span class=\"p\">]:</span> <span class=\"n\">ds</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">xr</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">open_dataset</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">filename</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"n\">In</span> <span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">12</span><span class=\"p\">]:</span> <span class=\"n\">ds</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">ds</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">assign_coords</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">time</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"n\">ds</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">time_bnds</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mean</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s1\">&#39;nbnd&#39;</span><span class=\"p\">))</span>\n</pre></div>\n\n\n<p>You may want to preserve your original attributes because xarray seems to throw those away during the <code> ds = ds.assign_coords(time=ds.time_bnds.mean('nbnd'))</code></p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><span class=\"n\">In</span> <span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">13</span><span class=\"p\">]:</span> <span class=\"n\">ds</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">time</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">attrs</span>\n<span class=\"n\">Out</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">13</span><span class=\"p\">]:</span> <span class=\"p\">{}</span>\n</pre></div>",
